  % No DOI available -- self-published blog series
  note      = {Personal blog/website; not peer-reviewed. Author identity unverified.},
  abstract  = {This self-published philosophical work argues that reality has a grammar in the sense of "organised potential" — not because reality is language or linguistic in nature, but because the central question is "how is reality organised so that particular possibilities become available?" The author distinguishes grammar-as-organised-potential from grammar-as-syntactic-rules, arguing that the former is ontologically prior: reality's grammar is the structure that determines which possibilities can become actual, under what conditions, and in what order. The blog series develops this across multiple posts, examining how possibility, becoming, and actualization relate to organizational structure.},
  annotation  = {For HUMMBL, this framing is foundational to the Base120 concept and the P (projection) and SY (synthesis) transformations: Base120 is not a language for describing reality but a grammar of organized potential — a system that encodes which cognitive transformations are possible, under what conditions, and in what sequence. The work reframes reasoning as the actualization of grammatically available possibilities rather than the manipulation of pre-given propositions.},
  keywords  = {possibility, becoming, grammar of reality, organised potential, ontology, actualization, HUMMBL:P, HUMMBL:SY, HUMMBL:DE, HUMMBL:RE, HUMMBL:CO}
